Figure S3a: Identifying ATAC regions with differential H3K27Ac

Project: Enhancer identification

Author: Jeff Johnston

Generated: Wed Aug 24 2016, 07:48 PM

Overview

Outline:

  • Call ATAC peaks in wild-type whole-embryo 2-4h sample
  • Divide into groups: near TSS, inside gene, intergenic
  • Measure H3K27Ac signal in 1kb window around summit for Toll10b and gd7
  • Identify peaks with differential H3K27Ac (DESeq2)

Peak calling

MACS2 was run on the combined two replicates of ATAC-seq in 2-4h embryos, yielding the following number of peaks:

Sample Peaks
ATAC 2-4h 29,510

Classify peaks by proximity to nearest gene

Each peak will be assigned to one of the following categories:

  • TSS (within 1kb of a TSS)
  • Inside gene
  • Intergenic
classification Count
Inside_Gene 12,549
Intergenic 3,944
TSS 13,017

DESeq

Using the H3K27Ac read counts for two replicates each of Toll10b and gd7 samples, we call differentially-bound peaks using DESeq2. This results in the following numbers of peaks (adjusted p-value < 0.01):

classification No_Change Up_gd7 Up_Toll10b
Inside_Gene 12,138 175 236
Intergenic 3,791 61 92
TSS 12,691 125 201

Below is a plot of the H3K27Ac signal at each ATAC region for the two tissues, highlighting those called significantly different by DESeq:

Of the 59 known enhancers, 29 overlap an ATAC differential H3K27Ac region.

Including only non-TSS regions, we detect differential H3K27Ac at 16 known enhancers.
